                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Fact; enchanters are for all intent worthless for direct DPS.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Ignoring the fact a Dire Charmed pet can do 100+ dps, we can still chain cast Insanity and Dementia. Without focus effects, including Improved Damage or Spell Haste, those two nukes will do 1875 damage every 17 seconds (6 second cast time, 2.5 second refresh time), or 110 dps. Add in spell haste, mana preservation, and improved damage, and that dps total goes up, and we can keep it up for quite a while. So not "worthless" by any means.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Add to that we basically run around in pajamas.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Pish posh. My enchanter has 2200 hit points and 750 AC unbuffed, and that's with more than one slot horribly underdeveloped. Plus, that's what's called a 'trade off'. If enchanters could run around in plate mail with tank level hit points, then the challenge of EQ would be reduced any more.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Our offense and defense skills max out before we hit 30th level.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Yes, because many int. casters melee their way into the 60s. <img src="images/smiles/icon_wink.gif" alt="icon_wink.gif" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">By the time we are looking at the high end game it doesn't matter how great the dps of a staff is that we have, we'll never hit anything with it.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
And this is surprising how? Although I guess Gandalf in LotRs might give people who start EQ these days a bad impression. "I wanna be a wizard that can dual wield!"
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Only, in the last four expansions time and time again our abilities to effect the circumstances have been nerfed.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
But we're still the best at doing it. Or near the best. We can still pacify, mez, root, charm, stun, debuff, mana tap, etc. Simply because we cannot affect things as well or as powerfully as we once did means nothing. We still have a lot to do.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Quote: 
<br />
Haste spells are also the domain of the enchanter, providing incredible boosts in attack speed for members of their group 
<br />

<br />

<br />
Okay second spell line mentioned in the write up, and it too is over shadowed by other classes.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
That's crazy talk. Craaaazy talk. We have the longest lasting haste spell. We have the highest percentage haste spell. We have haste spells with an attack component to it, an AC and agility component.
<br />

<br />
In addition, we have illusion spells like NDT and boon and imp that add nice additional dps to melee classes.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Third item in the list. Only all illusions are nerfed, and now several racial illusions are insanely hard to obtain. And it's not like most illusions have any kind of real utility.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Wha'? We get Permenant Illusion, which lets us run around with 62 percent sow speed for 25 hours. Simply because you can buy a gnome illusion from a shaman for 100 plat doesn't mean our illusions are 'nerfed'. Plus who wants utility? Illusions are fun, and were never meant to be powerful or game changing. They're there for colour and effect, not to allow us to solo or group better.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Quote: 
<br />
In battle, enchanters are able to bring order to chaotic situations, often saving their group in a fight that would otherwise be lost. Enchanters possess the ability to mesmerize their enemies, temporarily removing them from a battle.  
<br />

<br />
Only starting with Velious (because SoE badly created the avatar script), all giants are un-mezzable. This trend has been used to 'correct' anything SoE has made a mistake on. The result being more often then not, when mezz really would "save thier group", enchanters find that all they have done is aggro an NPC that will kill them (remember the guy only wears pajamas) in three hits.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Until you learn and adjust after the first time that happens, and then root or charm the add instead of trying to mez.
<br />

<br />
Another way to think of it - simply because you can't root or snare sentries in HoH doesn't mean snare is now a useless spell.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Quote: 
<br />
Attack slowing spells are also a specialty, dramatically lowering the speed of a monster's attacks for a period of time 
<br />

<br />
Okay, at least on Nameless, the trend is to look for a Shaman first, and an Enchanter only if no shaman are available for slowing. Shaman as deamed to be better at it, they have good AC and HP, and better defense, the result is when they do pull agro for a slow, they live through it.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I have Arcane Rune and Eldritch Rune. That's 3k hit points extra I have if I get aggro from a slow spell. /shrug I also have 5k hit points buffed. That's 8k hit points - Unless you're in a really shitty group, an enchanter will be able to easily live through aggro.
<br />

<br />
Plus, our slow is 5% lower then a shaman max slow. I don't know a group in the world that would hold out for a shaman to slow if an enchanter is available.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Quote: 
<br />
In many situations, enchanters can call upon powerful charm spells to subjugate the mind of a monster and command it to do the enchanter's bidding 
<br />

<br />
The reality is charm is and always has been only useful in carefully controlled situations. If that weren't the fact then back when there was only the old world, everyone would have been playing an enchanter. 
<br />

<br />
Now, with more and more creatures being given huge magic resists, and being flagged as uncharmable, lets face it, it's not just situational, it's pigeon holed out of usefulness entirely. 
<br />

<br />
Let's remember, charm was the back up for mezz in situations were encounters had already been nerfed by the mobs being un-mezzable. 
<br />

<br />
So this is in trueth a double nerf.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
True dat. Unfortunately, however, SoE has pooched the ball on a few things, and being able to charm 500+ point hits without some bit of danger would unbalance an already unbalanced game.
<br />

<br />
That being said, I charm solo to huge gains in HoH. I've duo'd tactics with a charmed pet and a druid. To say charm is useless is so wrong I don't even know where to begin.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Okay quick summary: 
<br />

<br />
Enchanter crowd control is the combination of; stuns, mezzes, charms, and roots. 
<br />
 - Stun is nerfed. 
<br />
 - Mez is nerfed. 
<br />
 - Charm is nerfed. 
<br />
 * Root is left. It's however as common as dirt in other classes.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Stun is 'nerfed' only past level 55. And we still get a couple of options (Color Cloud and WoM) to use instead. And simply because some mobs are immune to stun or mez means nothing. I mean, come on. If every mez was a guaranteed success, and nothing could resist, wtf would be the point?
<br />

<br />
Mez is not nerfed. A few mobs resist, and a few mobs have high resists that make it more difficult to land a mez. See above.
<br />

<br />
Charm is most definately not nerfed. See above.
<br />

<br />
Root is still good, although it's 'nerfed' as well because not every mob can be rooted.
<br />

<br />
Don't forget that we also get mem blur by the way. Although that's probably nerfed because it doesn't work 100% of the time. <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" />
